external_knowledge:
- A command is an action applied to a specific axis in a system;
- Performance metrics include execution and completion times, actual speed, and torque;
- Overrides are changes made to commands, recorded with the time and description of the override, and the operator who performed it;
- The average actual speed is calculated for each axis based on the performance metrics.

- Commands with higher `avg_actual_speed` are considered faster;
- Commands with higher `avg_actual_torque` are considered more powerful;
- The `speed_rank` is used to determine the order of commands based on their average speed.

- "Most recent command" refers to the command with the latest `executed_by_robot_at` timestamp for each robot;
- "Actual speed" is the speed achieved during the execution of the command, as recorded in the `performance_metrics` table;
- "Axis name" is the name of the mechanical axis on which the command was executed;
- "Operator name" is the full name of the operator who executed the command;
- "Robot model" is the specific model of the robot that executed the command.

- High-performance axes are those with a maximum speed greater than 50 and a maximum torque greater than 100;
- The actual speed during execution should be greater than 80, and the actual torque should be greater than 50;
- Commands are considered successful if they have a status of 'success';
- A command is not overridden if there is no override record, or if the override occurred after the command was executed.

- "average execution time" is calculated by averaging the execution times of commands for each axis on each day;
- "overall average execution time" is the average of all average execution times across all axes;
- "axes" refer to the different axes in the system to which commands are applied.

- 'sprint faster than a thousand' refers to the maximum speed being greater than 1000.0;
- 'average pace' refers to the average speed of the commands;
- 'general stride of all commands' refers to the average speed of all commands in the `commands` table.

- The `command_type` refers to the type of command (e.g., move, rotate);
- The `execution_time` is the timestamp when the command was executed;
- The query is looking for the earliest execution time among all command types.

- "Robot 1" refers to the robot with an ID of 1;
- "Non-zero torque limit" refers to commands with a torque limit greater than 0;
- "Flexible score" refers to commands that are overrideable (overrideable status of 1);
- "Average performance duration longer than a minute" refers to the average time difference between completion and execution times being greater than 30 seconds (half a minute).

sql:
SELECT COUNT(command_id) 
FROM commands 
WHERE overrideable = 1 AND speed > (SELECT AVG(speed) FROM commands);

SELECT pm.command_id
FROM performance_metrics pm
WHERE pm.actual_speed = (SELECT MAX(actual_speed) FROM performance_metrics);

SELECT command_id, execution_time
FROM command_logs
WHERE status = 'success';

SELECT axis_name, max_speed
FROM axes
ORDER BY max_speed DESC;

external_knowledge:
- A "command" in this context is an instruction given to a robot, which can be thought of as a task or action;
- An "overridden command" is a command that was modified or changed after it was initially issued;
- The "override percentage" is the ratio of overridden commands to the total commands executed by a robot, expressed as a percentage;
- The robots are metaphorically described as performers in a symphony, where the commands are the notes they play, and overridden commands are notes they modify.

- "command executions" refer to the operations performed by robots on specific axes;
- "average speed" is calculated by dividing the total actual speed by the number of executions;
- "axis" is a part of the robotic system where commands are applied.

sql:
SELECT SUM(actual_speed) AS cumulative_speed
FROM performance_metrics
WHERE command_id = 1;

SELECT COUNT(log_id) 
FROM command_logs 
WHERE status = 'success' AND operator_id = 1;

SELECT AVG(actual_torque) 
FROM performance_metrics 
WHERE robot_id = (SELECT robot_id FROM robots WHERE robot_name = 'Robot B');

SELECT axis_name, description
FROM axes
WHERE max_speed > 200.0 AND axis_name LIKE '%Secondary%';

